<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900710-0010</DOCNO><DOCID>900710-0010.</DOCID><HL>   Hughes Aircraft Chairman   Denies Budget Allegations</HL><DATE>07/10/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18</SO><CO>   GM GMH</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Hughes Aircraft Co. Chairman Malcolm R.Currie denied that he improperly handled Pentagon budgetsecrets in the early 1980s, maintaining that such allegationsare based on &quot;innunendoes and hearsay.&quot;   In response to a Wall Street Journal story last Fridayabout an ongoing federal grand jury probe of illegalgathering and swapping of Pentagon budget documents, Mr.Currie issued a letter to employees of Hughes, a unit ofGeneral Motors Corp. In the five-paragraph letter, Mr. Curriesaid, &quot;I did not know or approve of the unlawful activitiesin question.&quot; The letter also said that prosecutors &quot;advisedus that I am not a target of this criminal investigation.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Further, he said, &quot;I offered my testimony freely andvoluntarily&quot; to federal investigators and no civil lawsuit is&quot;contemplated against Hughes or myself&quot; by the government.   Mr. Currie declined to be interviewed for last Friday'sJournal story. The company issued a brief comment saying thatMr. Currie &quot;did not have any knowledge&quot; of illegal conduct bya Hughes employee convicted last month of trafficking inbootlegged Pentagon documents.   The story said Mr. Currie had been under criminalinvestigation, and had been interviewed by federalinvestigators, but wasn't a target of the grand jury inquiry.Law enforcement officials in Washington couldn't be reachedyesterday, but repeatedly have indicated that they haven'truled out some sort of civil action against Mr. Currie andothers.</TEXT></DOC>